 from immediate neighbors, (2) costs of\nmaintaining links with immediate neighbors, (3) benefits from indirect\nneighbors, (4) bridging benefits, and (5) network entry fee. Based on this\nmodel, we analyze relevant network topologies such as star graph, complete\ngraph, bipartite Turan graph, and multiple stars with interconnected centers,\nand derive a set of sufficient conditions under which these topologies emerge\nas pairwise stable networks. We also study the social welfare properties of the\nabove topologies.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 9 Jan 2012 01:27:47 GMT"},{"version":"v10","created":"Thu, 9 Oct 2014 16:42:20 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Sun, 29 Jan 2012 19:21:46 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Tue, 21 Feb 2012 22:08:36 GMT"},{"version":"v4","created":"Wed, 11 Jul 2012 21:06:38 GMT"},{"version":"v5","created":"Mon, 24 Sep 2012 20:33:02 GMT"},{"version":"v6","created":"Thu, 29 Nov 2012 15:12:04 GMT"},{"version":"v7","created":"Tue, 22 Jan 2013 19:50:52 GMT"},{"version":"v8","created":"Mon, 9 Sep 2013 18:43:15 GMT"},{"version":"v9","created":"Tue, 10 Sep 2013 06:02:09 GMT"}],"update_date":"2014-10-10"}
